bib.title: The Baghdad Atlas: A Relational Database Of Inelasticneutron-Scattering (N,N'Gamma) Data

free_txt: Journal publication for data
re-analysis and database.
Re-analysis of
Baghdad data. This report is relevant to all
subentries, as it presents a detailed description of
the methods by which the analysis to extract these
cross-sections was performed.
Reactor IRT-5000, in Baghdad.
A.S.Voyles, L.A.Bernstein, A.M.Hurst,
B.Pritychenko
BP: Added NIM/A article on database.
Using the gamma-ray intensity data (normalized to the
846.8-keV transition in 56Fe, as described in MONITOR),
the partial gamma-ray production cross section is
extracted for each observed transition in the Atlas.
This normalization is performed in a two-step fashion,
where the gamma line with the most reliable intensity
measurement is selected for each sample. This reference
line (identified in ANALYSIS for the subentry of each
sample) is in turn normalized to the 846.8-keV line in
56Fe (described in MONITOR) using data from Table 2,
p.25-27 in [1978DE41], where the relative intensity of
the 846.8-keV line in 56Fe is defined to be 100%. All
other lines belonging to each sample nucleus are in
turn normalized to their corresponding reference gamma
line. The magnitude of each reference line is itself
normalized to the flux-weighted
(26-FE-56(N,INL)26-FE-56) cross section for the first
2+ state in 56Fe, corresponding to 978.965 +/- 13.430
mb. The flux-weighted cross section was determined by
convolving the filtered IRT-5000 reactor spectrum (as
shown on page 14, figure 5 of this work [1978DE41])
with the ENDF/B-VIII.0 value for the
(26-FE-56(N,INL)26-FE-56) cross section to the first
2+ state. This cross section includes direct feeding of
the first 2+ state in 56Fe (MT=51), as well as feeding
via the discrete excited states of 56Fe
feeding contribution from the continuum (MT=91). The
continuum contribution is an estimate based on the
observed feeding from discrete states relative to the
cross-section summation from direct and discrete-level
feeding contributions. Excitation energies (E-EXC),
gamma-ray energies (E-GAMMA), and branching ratios (BR)
are taken from, or deduced using information in, ENSDF.
These are summarized in a table below. A small
correction (98.85(3)% branching ratio) corresponding to
the beta minus decay of 56Mn formed in the
been accounted for in the determination of the flux-
weighted cross section. No neutron-gamma angular
correlation corrections appear to have been performed
by the authors of [1978DE41].
File   E-EXC (keV)   E-GAMMA (keV)      BR
Energy and efficiency calibrations of the 30
cm**3 Ge(Li) spectrometer were performed using a
variety of standard radioactive sources (75Se, 182Ta,
110Ag, 72Ga, 140La, 24Na, and 134Cs) and an additional
reaction source (14-SI-28(N,G)14-SI-29) for energies
below and above 3 MeV, respectively, using state-of-
the-art values for these sources as of 1978.
Corrections are also made for gamma-ray self absorption
within the samples. This single detector at 90 degrees
was used for most experiments, with the measurements on
chlorine (subentry 14521014), scandium (14521017),
bromine (14521031), lutetium (14521089), osmium
(14521097), iridium (14521098), and tellurium
(subentries 14521061 -- 14521065) instead using a
higher-resolution 40 cm**3 Ge(Li) spectrometer,
calibrated in the same fashion. The 30 cm**3 detector
resolution is quoted as initially being 3.8 keV at 1.2
MeV, degrading down to 8 keV over the course of
measurements due to radiation damage, and the 40 cm**3
detector resolution is quoted as 2 keV at 1.2 MeV.
Background spectra for both detectors were measured
using samples of graphite and beryllium, with the
energies and intensities of all background lines shown
on page 25, table 1 of this work [1978DE41]. There is
no indication in [1978DE41] that any angular
correlation corrections were applied to the gamma-ray
intensities.
The total uncertainties of the measurements
were calculated according to Gaussian error
propagation.
The total uncertainty in the
(26-FE-56(N,INL)26-FE-56) cross section to the first
2+ state in 56Fe (MT=51). Includes Gaussian propagated
contributions due to branching-ratio uncertainties
corresponding to the feeding of the 1st 2+ state in
56Fe from discrete excited states
estimated 50% uncertainty in the assumed branching
ratio for the continuum (MT=91) feeding contribution,
as described in ANALYSIS. An additional correction is
made for the population of the 846.8 keV transition
from the decay of 56Mn produced in the 56Fe(n,p)
reaction channel.
Relative gamma-ray transition intensity.
Uncertainty includes statistical error (with 95%
probability) folded with uncertainties due to the
spectrometer efficiency, as described in DETECTOR, and
a gamma-ray self-absorption term.
Normalization factor for determination of
absolute partial gamma-ray cross sections. Uncertainty
includes a statistical error (with 95% probability)
folded with uncertainties due to efficiency
determination of spectrometer, as described in
DETECTOR, and gamma-ray self-absorption.
Total uncertainty in gamma-ray energy,
including statistics errors (with 95% probability),
errors due to calibration, and non-linearity of the
spectroscopic tract for Egamma.
Reactor IRT-5000, in Baghdad.
A flux-average neutron energy of approximately
The data was taken in a broad, fast IRT-5000 reactor
spectrum that was filtered to remove thermal
contributions. The authors characterized the spectrum
as being monotonically decreasing with increasing
neutron energy, and the spectrum can be described
approximately by a flux distribution phi(En) ~= exp(-
0.7473 En) for neutron energies above 2 MeV, ranging
from 0.5 - 10 MeV, with a flux-average neutron energy
of approximately 1.17 MeV, as shown on page 14, figure
5 of this work [1978DE41].
Samples were irradiated using a Cd-
filtered reactor neutron spectrum from an IRT-5000
reactor based at the Al-Tuwaitha research facility
outside of Baghdad, Iraq in the 1970s, as described in
INC-SPECT. Gamma-ray intensities were measured using a
Ge(Li) detector, as described in DETECTOR, shielded
with iron (5 cm), paraffin with boron carbide (8 cm),
lead (10 cm), and 6Li (3 mm). Gamma rays passing to the
detector from the target were filtered from fast
neutrons with a 6.8 g/cm**2 layer of lithium hydride
(LiH).
All intensities
were measured relative to the intensity of the
846.8-keV 1st 2+ --> G.S. 0+ gamma-ray transition in
56Fe from the Fe-56(n,ng) reaction.

authors of LBNL-1007259, using the methods it
describes. Cross sections derived from gamma-ray
intensities taken from table on pages 33
of this work [1978DE41], as described in ANALYSIS.
